## Recovery Protocol Triggers

| Signal | Protocol | Duration |
|--------|----------|----------|
| Readiness score below 50 for 2+ days | Mandatory deload or rest days | Until readiness returns above 60 |
| Persistent soreness in a muscle group > 72 hours | Avoid loading that group; add foam rolling and light stretching | Until soreness resolves to 3/10 or below |
| Resting HR elevated > 5 bpm above baseline for 3+ days | Reduce all training volume 50%; prioritize sleep | 3-5 days minimum |
| HRV trend declining for 5+ days | Switch to active recovery sessions only | Until HRV stabilizes at baseline |
| Joint pain (sharp, not muscular DOMS) | Stop loading that joint; seek professional assessment | Until cleared |
| Mood and motivation declining alongside training metrics | Full deload week with emphasis on enjoyable, unstructured movement | 5-7 days |

## Injury Prevention Guidelines

| Area | Strategy | Frequency |
|------|----------|-----------|
| Warm-up | 5-10 min progressive: general movement, specific activation, ramp-up sets | Every session |
| Push/pull balance | Track weekly volume parity between pushing and pulling movements within 10% | Weekly audit |
| Posterior chain work | Include glute, hamstring, and upper back exercises every training day | Every session |
| Mobility work | Target individual restrictions (hip, thoracic spine, ankle, shoulder) | Minimum 3x/week |
| Load management | Stay within 10% weekly volume increase; use RPE to auto-regulate | Per session |
| Cool-down | 5 min light movement + static stretching for worked muscle groups | Every session |

## Common Pitfalls

### 1. Program Hopping

Wrong: Switch training programs every 2-3 weeks because progress is not immediately visible.

Right: Commit to a well-designed program for a minimum of 6-8 weeks before evaluating effectiveness. Adaptation takes time.

### 2. Ignoring Readiness Signals

Wrong: Follow the program exactly as written regardless of sleep quality, stress, or soreness.

Right: Use readiness scores to auto-regulate daily intensity. The program is a plan, not a contract. Adjust based on the body's signals.

### 3. Skipping Deloads

Wrong: Train at maximum intensity for 12+ weeks without a planned recovery week.

Right: Schedule deload weeks every 4-8 weeks depending on training experience. Fitness is built during recovery, not during the workout.

### 4. Cardio as Punishment

Wrong: Add extra cardio sessions as punishment for dietary lapses or to "earn" food.

Right: Program cardio for cardiovascular health, endurance, and recovery. Separate exercise from food morality entirely.

### 5. Neglecting Movement Quality

Wrong: Add weight to the bar when the current load produces compensatory movement patterns.

Right: Film key lifts periodically. Only progress load when form is consistent across all working sets. Technique is a long-term investment in injury-free training.
